
Pods are ephemeral — they get created, destroyed, and 
rescheduled with new IP addresses. 

This makes it impractical for other applications to 
connect to them directly using IP addresses.

Services solve this problem by providing a stable 
network endpoint (DNS name + IP address) that routes 
traffic to a dynamic set of Pods.


Key concepts:

  * A Service uses label selectors to find the Pods it 
    should send traffic to.

  * Kubernetes automatically creates and updates Endpoints 
    (or the newer EndpointSlices) that track the actual 
    Pod IPs and ports.

  * There are four main Service types:

      * ClusterIP (default): Only reachable from inside 
        the cluster.

      * NodePort: Exposes the service on a static port 
        on every node’s IP.

      * LoadBalancer: Provisions an external load balancer 
        (cloud providers) or uses MetalLB on bare metal or
        kind.

      * ExternalName: Maps a service to an external DNS 
        name.


Services are one of the most fundamental networking primitives 
in Kubernetes. Almost everything else (Ingress, Gateway API, 
Skupper, etc.) builds on top of them.




Exercise 1:  Create a Deployment and expose it with a 
             ClusterIP Service
-----------------------------------------------------------------

cat <<EOF | kubectl apply -f -
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: web
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: web
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: web
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx
        image: nginx:alpine
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: web
spec:
  selector:
    app: web
  ports:
  - port: 80
    targetPort: 80
EOF

# Verify
kubectl get svc web
kubectl get endpoints web
kubectl get pods -l app=web



